    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-02-10T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-02-10T14:00:00-05:00" n="17"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d17">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15a3/684c: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the Chairman of the American Delegation</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stimson</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-02-10T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 10, 1930—2 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>84. There was one other matter, in discussing your offer further with the
                    President before his departure for Florida, concerning which you probably
                    understand his wishes; at the risk, however, of repetition we again explain that
                    200,000 tons for destroyers seems to be a very high figure. Presumably it is now
                    being placed that high by you so that negotiations between Great Britain and
                    France may be left in <pb facs="0103" n="23" xml:id="pg_23"/> a better position;
                    the President hopes, however, that 150,000 tons will be the limit for the final
                    figure.</p>
                <p>In regard to your offer, the above is the last comment. It appears to us here
                    that your general strategy is correct; only those who will oppose whatever you
                    do are opposed to your plan.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Cotton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
